  "Idea": "This research proposes a systematic investigation into the ability of multilingual transformer models to perform zero-shot cross-lingual acceptability classification, with a focus on distinguishing between surface-level heuristics and genuine syntactic generalization—particularly in the context of Italian, a moderately resourced Romance language with significant syntactic divergence from English. While prior work has demonstrated that models can transfer semantic classifications across languages, acceptability judgments require sensitivity to complex syntactic constraints (e.g., subject-verb agreement, clitic placement, island effects) that are not always preserved across languages. We hypothesize that current multilingual models succeed in zero-shot settings not because they acquire deep syntactic knowledge, but because they exploit shallow, surface-level distributional cues that coincidentally align with acceptability in certain languages. To test this, we design a diagnostic dataset for Italian that pairs naturally occurring acceptable/unacceptable sentence pairs with minimally contrastive syntactic variants generated via linguistically grounded transformations (e.g., violating agreement, scrambling constituents, inserting extraction islands). These items are mapped to Universal Dependency edge types to quantify syntactic divergence from English. We then evaluate several multilingual models (e.g., mBERT, XLM-R, InfoXLM) in a zero-shot setup, where models are fine-tuned on English acceptability datasets (e.g., CoLA) and evaluated on our Italian diagnostic set. Crucially, we introduce a dual-axis evaluation: (1) accuracy on syntactically controlled contrasts, and (2) consistency of predictions across semantically equivalent but syntactically varied paraphrases (inspired by consistency-by-agreement). The latter measures whether the model makes stable grammaticality judgments regardless of surface variation. We further analyze model representations using p