  "Idea": "This research introduces a novel framework for improving zero-shot cross-lingual acceptability classification by explicitly disentangling syntactic and lexical-semantic representations in multilingual transformer models. While prior work has shown that models like XLM-R can transfer semantic classifications across languages, their performance on fine-grained syntactic tasks—such as grammaticality judgments—remains inconsistent, especially for structurally divergent languages like Italian. We argue that this limitation stems not merely from data scarcity, but from the entanglement of surface-level distributional patterns with deeper syntactic knowledge in model representations. To address this, we propose DisenSyn, a disentangled representation learning approach that separates syntactic structure (encoded via Universal Dependency trees) from lexical content during cross-lingual transfer. Our method involves three key innovations: (1) a dual-channel autoencoder that reconstructs sentences using separated syntactic and lexical latents, trained on parallel English-Italian treebanks; (2) a syntactic alignment module that maps dependency relations across languages using graph convolutional networks; and (3) a zero-shot acceptability classifier that operates solely on the disentangled syntactic channel, preventing reliance on language-specific surface cues. We evaluate DisenSyn on a newly curated Italian acceptability dataset featuring minimal pairs with controlled violations (e.g., subject-verb disagreement, illicit extraction), comparing it against standard zero-shot baselines (mBERT, XLM-R). Crucially, we measure not only accuracy but also syntactic fidelity—using probing classifiers and attention analysis—to determine whether improvements stem from genuine structural generalization. Additionally, we introduce a syntactic consistency metric: if multiple paraphrased versions of an ungrammatical sentence (with identical syntactic errors) receive consistent rejection, the model demonstrates robust syntactic reasoning. By integrating disentanglement into the architecture itself—not just post-hoc analysis—our work moves beyond diagnosis to intervention, offering a scalable solution for enhancing syntactic transfer in low-resource scenarios. The outcome will be both a principled framework for building more linguistically aware multilingual models and empirical evidence on the conditions under which syntactic generalization can succeed across languages.",
